intent: >
  Fix PR #26 review UX bug: a parse failure on expected_status_codes wiped
  the user's input on form redisplay, forcing them to retype their bad
  input from scratch to fix it.

slice: 13/13
kind: fix
behavior_change: none

reversibility: trivial

scope:
  declared:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "The @expected_status_codes_parse_error instance variable survives from the setter call through the validator and into the form re-render, because ActiveRecord doesn't reinstantiate the object between failed save and the controller's render :new"
  - "ERB's form.text_field reads the value: option and displays it verbatim, so returning the raw bad string from the display helper puts it directly in the input's value attribute"

specifications:
  - "expected_status_codes_for_display returns the raw @expected_status_codes_parse_error value (as a string) when a parse error is pending, otherwise the joined array or empty string"
  - "The display helper's return type is always String — a parse error converts to String via to_s (handles nil/empty input cases)"
  - "After a parse failure, the attribute is nil BUT the display helper returns the original bad input, so the user sees their own text on the re-rendered form alongside the validation error"

deviations_from_plan: >
  pr-review-driven slice. Pure UX fix, no architectural change.

addresses:
  - "#26"

trade_offs: >
  Stored the raw input in an instance variable rather than a transient
  model attribute or a separate error object. Cost: the display helper
  has hidden instance-variable state. Benefit: matches the existing
  setter's pattern (the setter already writes to @expected_status_codes_parse_error
  for the validator to read) and doesn't require a new column or a
  changed serialization format.

interfaces:
  consumed: []
  published:
    - "Site#expected_status_codes_for_display -> String (now preserves raw invalid input on parse failure)"

self_review:
  tests: >
    One new case: set an invalid string, call valid? to trigger the parse-
    error validator, assert (1) expected_status_codes is nil (setter stored
    nil on parse failure), (2) expected_status_codes_for_display returns
    the raw bad string, (3) errors[:expected_status_codes] is populated.
    All three assertions on one example because they're one flow — the
    user-facing round-trip.
  consistency: >
    The early-return pattern in expected_status_codes_for_display matches
    the early-return used in validate_expected_status_codes just above
    it — both read the same @expected_status_codes_parse_error ivar.
  metz: >
    Measured. site.rb grew from 123 lines (after Slice 12) to 128;
    method count unchanged at 8. expected_status_codes_for_display is
    now 4 body lines — under the 5-line rule.
  api: >
    Additive at the Ruby level: expected_status_codes_for_display now
    has a conditional branch that didn't exist before. Backwards
    compatible for any caller that was reading the helper when parse_error
    was absent.

confidence: high
reviewer_attention:
  - "app/models/site.rb:65-72"  # the conditional early-return that reads @expected_status_codes_parse_error
